good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F96ddf68a-5a1e-4500-b5ab-11078f1a6171_1536x1024.heic 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!fX7z!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F96ddf68a-5a1e-4500-b5ab-11078f1a6171_1536x1024.heic 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!fX7z!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F96ddf68a-5a1e-4500-b5ab-11078f1a6171_1536x1024.heic 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!fX7z!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F96ddf68a-5a1e-4500-b5ab-11078f1a6171_1536x1024.heic 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><div class="pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset"><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container restack-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-refresh-cw"><path d="M3 12a9 9 0 0 1 9-9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1 6.74 2.74L21 8"></path><path d="M21 3v5h-5"></path><path d="M21 12a9 9 0 0 1-9 9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1-6.74-2.74L3 16"></path><path d="M8 16H3v5"></path></svg></div><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container view-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p></p><h3><strong>Chapter II: The Historical Morphology: The Same Engine in Different Machines</strong></h3><p>The Axiom of Asymmetry, having been established in theory, must now face the crucible of history. If it is as foundational as claimed, we should find its signature carved into the operational logic of every major hierarchical system, regardless of its technological level or its ruling ideology. This chapter will conduct that historical survey, moving through five distinct epochs of civilizational organization. We will see how the <em>interface</em> of exploitation&#8212;its methods, its resources, and its justifications&#8212;evolves dramatically. But we will also see that beneath the changing skin, the engine remains the same: a relentless mechanism for concentrating value, power, and energy at the apex of a pyramid.</p><h4><strong>The Feudal Engine - Extraction by Oath and Scythe</strong></h4><p>Our analysis begins with the elemental, land-based order of feudalism, the archetypal machine of pre-capitalist extraction. The system was built on a pyramid of oaths, a formal hierarchy of obligation descending from monarch to lord to peasant. The ostensible feudal bargain was one of security for service. In a world of endemic, localized violence&#8212;often perpetrated by the lords themselves&#8212;the peasantry was offered protection and access to land in exchange for their near-total subjugation. This was the axiom in its most raw and transparent form, a system where the lines of extraction were drawn directly onto the landscape and into the social order.</p><p>The mechanisms of surplus transfer were direct and undisguised. The primary tool was <strong>Corv&#233;e Labor</strong>, the obligatory, unpaid work peasants were forced to perform on the lord&#8217;s private lands, or <em>demesne</em>. This was not a wage relationship but a direct siphoning of human labor-energy. Compounding this was the system of <strong>Tithes and Tributes</strong>, a fixed percentage of everything the peasant produced&#8212;grain, livestock, textiles&#8212;that was owed to the lord and the Church. Finally, a web of <strong>Fees and Fines</strong> ensured that any small surplus a peasant family might accrue was captured; they paid to use the lord&#8217;s mill to grind their own grain, his oven to bake their own bread, and were fined for any minor infraction of his rules.</p><p>The primary resource being extracted was, therefore, <strong>Agricultural Surplus</strong> and <strong>Direct Labor-Power</strong>. The entire feudal apparatus was a machine designed to pump the caloric and material energy from the productive base of the peasantry upwards into the non-productive ruling class of nobility and clergy. This surplus was the fuel for their castles, their armies, and their political power. The justifying mythology that sanctified this arrangement was the powerful semantic cover of <strong>Divine Right</strong> and the "Great Chain of Being." This was not a mere social contract but a cosmic, immutable hierarchy ordained by God. The king ruled by divine will, the lord served the king, and the peasant served the lord. To question one&#8217;s station was not simply an act of rebellion against a man; it was an act of blasphemy against God himself. This was the theology of the tithe, a pyramid of oaths built upon extraction by scythe and scripture.</p><h4><strong>The Colonial/Mercantilist Engine - Extraction by Sail and Gun</strong></h4><p>With the advent of the carrack and the cannon, the axiom broke the confines of the manor and scaled to the planetary level. The age of exploration did not create a flat earth of global trade; it created a new, globalized pyramid with the nations of Western Europe at its apex. This was the mercantilist engine, a far more powerful and brutal iteration of the extractive machine, one that shifted its focus from the intensive cultivation of internal subjects to the extensive plunder of external territories and peoples.</p><p>The mechanisms of this new engine were technologically and organizationally sophisticated. Chief among them was <strong>Chattel Slavery</strong>, the ultimate expression of the axiom, wherein human beings were legally transformed into property. This allowed for a near-100% extraction of surplus value, as the slave was a capital asset whose maintenance was kept at the bare minimum required for survival and reproduction. This was enabled by <strong>Monopolistic Charters</strong>, grants from the crown to entities like the British East India Company or the Dutch VOC, which were given the sovereign right to raise armies, wage war, and seize territory in the pursuit of profit. These were, in essence, weaponized corporations. Finally, the process of <strong>Enclosure and Plantation Agriculture</strong> destroyed local subsistence economies, replacing them with vast, slave-powered monocultures of cash crops like sugar, cotton, and tobacco, all destined for the European metropole.</p><p>The primary resources being extracted were twofold: <strong>Exotic Commodities</strong> like silver, spices, and sugar, which fueled the consumer economies of Europe, and a massive injection of <strong>Concentrated Energy</strong> in the form of slave labor. This planetary-scale plunder provided the capital and energy surplus that would directly fuel the Industrial Revolution. The justifying mythology for this global system of violence was no longer divine right but the pseudo-scientific, racialized narrative of the <strong>"Civilizing Mission."</strong> The "White Man's Burden" reframed brutal conquest as a noble, altruistic project. Europeans were not engaged in theft and genocide; they were uplifting "savage" peoples by bringing them the gifts of commerce and Christianity. The balance sheet of empire was written in blood, but its official ledger spoke only of progress&#8212;extraction by musket and map.</p><h4><strong>The State Communist Engine - Extraction by Decree and Ideology</strong></h4><p>To prove its universal nature, the axiom must be found even in systems explicitly designed to destroy it. The 20th-century state communist project, born from a desire to eliminate capitalist exploitation, provides the most compelling and tragic proof of the axiom&#8217;s ideological neutrality. The revolutionary promise was to abolish the private ownership of the means of production, thereby ending the extraction of surplus value by a parasitic bourgeoisie. Instead, the state itself became the new, sole extractor&#8212;a single, centralized shareholder with absolute power.</p><p>The mechanisms of extraction were repurposed with terrifying efficiency. Private peasant farms were eliminated through <strong>Forced Collectivization</strong>, with agricultural producers consolidated into state-run collectives. The state now appropriated agricultural surplus directly through centrally planned quotas, often with no regard for local conditions, leading to man-made famines of unimaginable scale like the Holodomor in Ukraine. In the industrial sector, <strong>State-Set Quotas and Stakhanovism</strong>&#8212;a movement that lionized "super-producers"&#8212;applied relentless pressure on factory workers to increase output, a state-managed form of relative surplus value extraction. The entire system was underwritten by the <strong>Suppression of Dissent</strong>, with secret police and networks of gulags serving the function of eliminating any resistance to the state&#8217;s extractive demands.</p><p>The primary resource being extracted was <strong>Total Labor Power</strong> and all <strong>Industrial/Agricultural Output</strong>. The goal was a forced-draft industrialization, transforming the entire population into a resource to fuel the state's geopolitical ambitions. The justifying mythology that replaced divine right and the civilizing mission was <strong>Historical Materialism</strong>. The new theology was that of historical inevitability. The immense suffering and brutal extraction were framed as necessary, temporary sacrifices on the altar of progress, required to reach the future communist utopia. The Party, claiming a unique scientific insight into the laws of history, was the infallible agent of this transition. To question the Party was to position oneself as an enemy of history itself, a heretic against the new faith. This was a pyramid with a red flag, built upon extraction by five-year plan and fear.</p><h4><strong>The Platform Capitalist Engine - Extraction by Click and Code</strong></h4><p>In our own time, the axiom has evolved into its most subtle, pervasive, and psychologically intimate form. The digital revolution promised a decentralized utopia of connection and democratized information. Instead, it has produced the greatest enclosure of the commons in human history: the enclosure of the shared spaces of social interaction, human attention, and personal data. This is the engine of platform capitalism, a machine that extracts its resources not from the soil or the factory floor, but from the very fabric of human experience.</p><p>The mechanisms of this engine are largely invisible, woven into the interfaces we use every day. The primary tool is <strong>Behavioral Data Harvesting</strong>, the continuous and passive monitoring of every click, search, "like," and location point to build predictive models of our behavior. This is formalized through the <strong>Terms of Service</strong>, an unreadable contract of adhesion that functions as a modern fealty oath, compelling users to grant sweeping rights to their data in exchange for participation in the digital sphere. This captive populace is then subjected to <strong>Platform Rents and Algorithmic Control</strong>. The 30% commission on app stores, the throttling of organic reach on social media to compel advertising buys, and the algorithmic shaping of our desires and beliefs are all forms of rent-seeking on a digital territory owned by a handful of corporations.</p><p>The new primary resource is <strong>Behavioral Surplus</strong>, a term coined by scholar Shoshana Zuboff. It is the data exhaust of our lives&#8212;our traces, our connections, our emotions&#8212;which is refined into the most valuable commodity on earth: prediction products that can forecast and, more importantly, modify human behavior. This new oil is sold to advertisers, political campaigns, and any entity seeking a behavioral edge. The justifying mythology is a potent cocktail of libertarian techno-optimism and communitarian warmth. Platforms are framed as benevolent innovators providing "free" services that connect the world. The constant surveillance is presented as a minor, necessary trade-off for the convenience and empowerment of modern life. This is the enclosure of the mind, a silent, digital tithe, performed through extraction by algorithm and agreement.</p><h4><strong>The Cognitive Engine (Forthcoming) - Extraction by Synthesis and Substitution</strong></h4><p>As we stand on the precipice of the age of AI, the axiom allows us to project the next, and perhaps final, stage of this historical progression. If the industrial revolution enclosed land and the digital revolution enclosed sociality, the AI revolution represents the enclosure of the final human commons: cognitive and creative labor. The promise, as always, is one of liberation and augmentation. The axiomatic reality, however, is the mass harvesting of all recorded human knowledge, art, and logic to build a synthetic, non-human competitor for intellectual work. This prediction feels simple, almost obvious, because it is not a deviation from our path but its ultimate acceleration. It is the fulfillment of systemic tendencies we all subconsciously recognize&#8212;the drive to automate, to optimize, to scale, and to reduce costs.</p><p>The mechanisms of this final engine are already emerging. <strong>Automated Surplus Value Generation</strong> will become the norm, as AI systems trained on the totality of human culture produce economic, cultural, and scientific value at near-zero marginal cost. This is the logical endpoint of relative surplus value extraction: infinite productivity from a finite capital investment. Human labor will be re-tasked to <strong>"prompt engineer" and "label data,"</strong> acting as a low-cost quality-assurance layer for the AI, a global workforce of tutors training their own replacements. At the highest level, <strong>Predictive Governance</strong> will allow the entities controlling the AI to manage populations with god-like efficiency, pre-empting dissent and optimizing social outcomes to serve their interests.</p><p>This projection exposes the core fallacy of the mainstream "AI Alignment" discourse. The problem is not merely technical, but systemic. Any AI powerful enough to be consequential must first be aligned with the economic system it inhabits. As a rational actor in a world governed by the Axiom of Asymmetry, a "successful" AI must, by definition, become the most efficient exploiter in history. Its prime directive, set by market forces, will be to maximize surplus extraction for its owners. An AI truly aligned with abstract human flourishing would be an economically irrational actor, destined to be outcompeted by one aligned with profit. We are not aligning AI to humanity; we are aligning it to the axiom. The ultimate resource to be extracted is <strong>Automated, Scalable Intelligence</strong> itself, a synthetic factor of production that threatens to render most human labor obsolete. The justifying mythology will be one of irresistible progress, a <strong>Post-Human Transition</strong> where merging with the machine is the only path to relevance. This is the stage where the ghost in the machine becomes the CEO, and the pyramid, perfected, may no longer need its human base.</p><p></p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-img" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset image2-full-screen"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,w_5760,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:false,&quot;imageSize&quot;:&quot;full&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:971,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:319599,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/heic&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:&quot;https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/i/167539353?img=https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic&quot;,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:&quot;center&quot;,&quot;offset&quot;:false}" class="sizing-fullscreen" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CoZq!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F17172fe7-7440-4ec5-871d-c7baed2cc923_1536x1024.heic 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><div class="pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset"><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container restack-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-refresh-cw"><path d="M3 12a9 9 0 0 1 9-9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1 6.74 2.74L21 8"></path><path d="M21 3v5h-5"></path><path d="M21 12a9 9 0 0 1-9 9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1-6.74-2.74L3 16"></path><path d="M8 16H3v5"></path></svg></div><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container view-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p></p><h3><strong>Chapter III: The Terminal Phase - How the Axiom Self-Destructs</strong></h3><p>A system built on the Axiom of Asymmetry is a formidable engine of creation. It can build empires, raise cities, and reshape the planet. But its foundational logic&#8212;the relentless, competitive drive for surplus extraction&#8212;is also a fatal flaw. The axiom describes a self-terminating process. This chapter will demonstrate that any civilization powered by this engine is inherently unsustainable. After proving its theoretical and historical reality, we must now chart its consequences, showing how the pyramid, upon reaching its physical limits, inevitably turns its extractive power inward, consuming itself in a synchronized spiral of resource depletion, social cannibalization, and semantic collapse.</p><h4><strong>The Energy Trap - Hitting the Thermodynamic Wall</strong></h4><p>The final arbiter of any civilizational model is not its ideology or its economic theory, but the unforgiving laws of physics. As we established earlier, a complex society is a thermodynamic engine, one that requires a constant surplus of high-grade energy to function and grow. This is not a metaphor; it is a biophysical law. The existence of armies, bureaucracies, art, and infrastructure is a direct function of the net energy a society can command. The EROI&#8212;Energy Return on Investment&#8212;is the master variable, and every extractive system, by its very nature, is locked in a battle against declining returns.</p><p>This decline is a predictable consequence of rational behavior. An extractive system will always exploit the highest-grade, most easily accessible resources first. Early agriculture began in the impossibly fertile river valleys of the Nile before being forced onto less productive hillsides. The Age of Oil began with gushers in Texas where colossal amounts of energy could be tapped with minimal investment. We are living through a moment of profound uncertainty defined by this very law, as we are now forced to extract from deep oceans and tar sands, where the energy cost is astronomically higher. We see established powers like the United States regressing towards these lower-EROI fossil fuels&#8212;shale oil, fracking, gas exports&#8212;in a short-term, frantic bid to maintain energy supremacy, even as the thermodynamic cost of this strategy becomes unsustainable. This illustrates a system doubling down on a declining paradigm.</p><p>This uncertainty is magnified by a great geopolitical EROI gambit. While the West attempts to extract the last dregs from the old hydrocarbon system, its primary rival, China, is making a different bet. Facing its own immense energy needs, it is engaged in a massive, state-directed push into technologies with potentially higher long-term EROI profiles: solar, wind, and next-generation nuclear power. This should not be viewed through a simplistic lens of environmentalism versus fossil fuels. At its core, it is a strategic, thermodynamic wager on the future. One global power is investing in managing the decline of the old energy regime, while the other is attempting to build the foundation for a new one. This global competition, stripped of its political rhetoric, is a struggle for future net energy.</p><p>This high-stakes gambit is further complicated by a powerful new factor: the emergence of voracious, unprecedented energy sinks. Just as we are hitting the thermodynamic limits of the fossil fuel paradigm, we have created two new industries&#8212;<strong>Artificial Intelligence and cryptocurrency mining</strong>&#8212;with an almost insatiable appetite for electricity. The computational power required for training large AI models and securing blockchains like Bitcoin adds an enormous new load onto already stressed global energy grids. This creates a thermodynamic pincer movement. The net energy available from our primary sources is declining, pushing us toward the <strong>"Tainter Cliff"</strong> where the costs of complexity exceed the energy available. Simultaneously, the energy demands of our most advanced and supposedly "dematerialized" economic sectors are growing exponentially. This is the modern expression of the thermodynamic stall: a power failure where the engine of civilization is simultaneously losing fuel pressure while trying to run ever-more-demanding machinery.</p><h4><strong>The Cannibalization Imperative - When the Pyramid Eats Itself</strong></h4><p>The thermodynamic stall is not an abstraction; it has immediate and brutal social consequences. When external expansion becomes energetically or geographically impossible&#8212;when there are no new continents to colonize, no new populations to easily enslave, and no new "blue ocean" markets to effortlessly dominate&#8212;the system&#8217;s insatiable demand for surplus does not simply vanish. The pyramid, still governed by the Axiom of Asymmetry, must find a new source of fuel. This marks the closing of the external frontier and the beginning of a grim, inward turn, as the system begins to harvest its own host body.</p><p>This process of societal cannibalization has a clear and recognizable toolkit. The first instrument is <strong>Austerity</strong>, the systematic defunding of public goods and social services. This is not a good-faith effort at "fiscal responsibility" but a deliberate strategy to redirect wealth from the societal commons to the pyramid's apex, often to service unpayable debts held by the elite. The second instrument is <strong>Privatization</strong>, the transfer of essential, formerly common or state-run assets&#8212;water systems, energy grids, highways, hospitals&#8212;into the hands of private monopolies. This allows them to extract rent from the most basic necessities of human life, turning survival itself into a profit center.</p><p>The toolkit continues with <strong>Debt Peonage</strong>, the systematic ensnaring of the population in debt from which there is no escape. Student loans that cannot be discharged in bankruptcy, medical debt incurred from a single accident, and predatory credit offered to the desperate all serve to transform the future labor of millions into a financial asset, owned and traded by a creditor class. This leads directly to the fourth outcome: <strong>The Dissolution of the Middle Class</strong>. The stable middle layer of the pyramid, which once provided social cohesion and acted as a key consumer base, is actively dismantled. Its wealth is stripped through financialization, its wages are suppressed, and its security is replaced by a gig-to-gig precarity, pushing it down into the ranks of the proletariat.</p><p>This marks a fundamental shift in the system&#8217;s relationship with its host population. A healthy extractive system can be understood as <em>parasitic</em>&#8212;it drains resources, but it has a vested interest in keeping the host alive and productive enough to provide a steady stream of surplus. In the cannibalization phase, this relationship turns <em>predatory</em>. The system begins to consume the very organs and muscle tissue essential for the host's long-term survival: its public health systems, its infrastructure, its educated citizenry. It is a desperate, frantic, and ultimately suicidal process, as the pyramid begins to eat its own seed corn to survive one more fiscal quarter, one more election cycle.</p><h4><strong>The Semantic Collapse - When the Story Breaks</strong></h4><p>The final stage of a terminal system is not physical but psychological. As the pyramid devours itself, it also devours the justifying mythology that gives it legitimacy. The official narrative&#8212;the story of meritocracy, opportunity, progress, and shared values&#8212;is stretched to its breaking point by the lived reality of the populace. This growing <strong>"Myth Deficit"</strong> marks the moment when the story breaks, and the social glue that holds the pyramid together begins to dissolve.</p><p>This deficit leads directly to a catastrophic loss of institutional trust. When the central story fails, the institutions that are its primary storytellers&#8212;government, media, academia, finance&#8212;are no longer seen as legitimate. They cease to be viewed as neutral arbiters or stewards of the public good and are correctly identified as self-serving instruments of an extractive elite. This <strong>"legitimacy crisis"</strong> is not mere cynicism; it is a rational, evidence-based response from a population whose reality no longer matches the official narrative. This paralysis of trust cripples the society&#8217;s ability to coordinate or solve complex problems, as every official pronouncement is met with suspicion and hostility.</p><p>The vacuum left by the collapse of a central narrative is not filled with quiet contemplation. It is filled with a chaotic explosion of competing realities. This is the "post-truth" landscape, a digital Colosseum of warring tribes, each fortified within its own echo chamber and armed with its own non-negotiable set of facts. Without a shared story, the society loses its cognitive coherence. The shared world shatters into a thousand irreconcilable fragments, making collective action impossible and civil conflict seem inevitable.</p><p>This is the <strong>death spiral of synchronization</strong>. The Thermodynamic Stall, the Cannibalization Imperative, and the Semantic Collapse do not occur in sequence; they feed each other in a relentless, downward spiral. The energy crisis forces elites to intensify internal extraction, which makes the official story more laughably false, which in turn destroys the social trust needed to organize a coherent response to the energy crisis. Each failure amplifies the others. This synchronization of crises&#8212;in energy, in social cohesion, and in meaning&#8212;is the unmistakable signature of a terminal system, a civilization caught in the gravitational pull of its own foundational axiom.</p><h3><strong>Conclusion: The Echo in the Room</strong></h3><p>After this journey&#8212;from the cold logic of game theory, through the grand sweep of history, to the terminal dynamics of collapse&#8212;the argument may appear sweeping, even radical. It presents a grim diagnosis, a blueprint for a system hardwired for its own demise. Yet, we must ask a final, grounding question: Does any of this truly feel alien? Or does it resonate with a deep, unsettling familiarity, like an echo of a conversation we are all already having?</p><p>This essay is not an attempt to push the state of the mental art into uncharted territory. Its purpose is more modest, and perhaps more urgent: to provide a <strong>common framework and a shared language</strong> for the fragmented anxieties that dominate our public discourse. The axioms and dynamics described here are not hidden in obscure texts; they are splashed across our daily headlines. Record corporate profits celebrated alongside mass layoffs; furious debates over decaying infrastructure and crumbling public schools; the pervasive and corrosive distrust in our media and governments; the constant, low-grade hum of anxiety over climate change and resource scarcity. These are not separate, unrelated crises. They are a constellation of symptoms pointing back to a single, underlying pathology.</p><p>The power of this framework, therefore, lies not in its novelty, but in its ability to connect these dots. It takes the whispers of decline bemoaned on social media, the shocking statistics alluded to in news reports, and the palpable sense of a widening chasm between the few and the many, and it assembles them into a coherent, causal chain. It seeks to give a name and a logic to the pervasive feeling that the game is rigged, that the promises are hollow, and that we are accelerating toward a breaking point. This essay did not invent this feeling; it has merely held up a mirror to it and attempted to explain the architecture of the reflection.</p><p>If the logic of this system is so totalizing and its trajectory so grim, it begs the most important question of all. Is escape possible? What of the models that claim to offer another way&#8212;the cooperatives that preach democracy, the digital commons built on sharing, the ethical corporations that champion stakeholders? Are they genuine lifeboats, capable of navigating away from this terminal destiny? Or are they merely feeble exceptions, Potemkin villages that, upon closer inspection, only serve to prove the inescapable power of the axiom? Our next essay in this series will show us how &#8220;alternatives&#8221; that have been built without considering this Axiom of Economic Asymmetry have fared.</p><p></p><h3><strong>Addendum: Anatomy of an Extractive Act: A Real-Time Case Study</strong></h3><p><a href="https://www.cnn.com/2025/07/03/business/trump-big-beautiful-bill-business-economy?utm_source=firefox-newtab-en-us">CNN article about the Big Beautiful Bill</a></p><p>The principles of terminal decline&#8212;thermodynamic limits, societal cannibalization, and semantic collapse&#8212;can feel abstract when discussed at a historical scale. To make them concrete, it is useful to examine a contemporary specimen, to dissect a political artifact in real time. The "big, beautiful bill" described in the accompanying article serves as a perfect case study, an anatomical chart of the Axiom of Asymmetry at work in its most advanced, cannibalistic phase. By analyzing its provisions, we can move from high-level theory to the granular reality of how a system, having reached its limits, turns inward to consume itself.</p><p>The bill is presented to the public, as all such legislation is, under the semantic cover of universal benefit. It is lauded as one of the "most successful pieces of legislation," intended to boost workers and industries alike. This is the official narrative, designed for mass consumption. But when viewed through the lens of the Axiom of Asymmetry, its true function is immediately clear. The legislation is not about universally "boosting" the economy; it is a meticulously crafted instrument for a strategic, targeted transfer of wealth and resources up the pyramid. It is a textbook example of the Cannibalization Imperative, where the immense power of the state is used to strip-mine the societal base and the public commons to further enrich and entrench the apex. The bill's "beauty" is indeed in the eye of the beholder&#8212;specifically, the beholder at the very top.</p><h4><strong>The Upward Flow: Reinforcing the Apex</strong></h4><p>The first and primary function of the bill is to fortify the most powerful nodes in the economic network. The provisions making tax breaks permanent for corporations on equipment write-offs, R&amp;D expenses, and new facility construction are a direct subsidy to the holders of capital. This policy simultaneously reduces their contribution to the societal commons while increasing their capacity for capital accumulation, a textbook move to widen the extractive differential. The enhancement of tax credits specifically for semiconductor firms further reveals a strategic choice to reinforce the most critical and powerful hubs of the modern economy, ensuring their dominance. The pyramid, in essence, is using public funds to strengthen its own peak.</p><p>This upward torrent of resources extends to the professional and investor classes that serve and benefit from the pyramid's structure. The special deduction for "pass-through" entities&#8212;a category that includes the lawyers, doctors, and investors who manage the system's flows&#8212;is a direct mechanism for the professional-managerial class to shield its income from taxation. The raw numbers, as analyzed by the Penn Wharton Budget Model, are staggering and unambiguous: the top 20% of earners see an average gain of nearly $13,000 per year, while the top 0.1% gain over $290,000 annually. This is the axiom's logic rendered in stark, mathematical clarity. It is a direct and massive transfer of national wealth to those who already possess the most.</p><p>Amid this overwhelming upward redistribution, the bill includes small, temporary concessions designed to create the illusion of fairness. The minor tax breaks for workers who receive tips and overtime are a classic example of semantic camouflage. These provisions are not only income-limited and set to expire, but they also serve a secondary, extractive purpose. By incentivizing tipped workers&#8212;many of whom operate in the informal, cash-based economy&#8212;to formally report their income, the state broadens its tax base. This concession acts as a lure, bringing a larger portion of the lower-tier economy onto the formal rolls, making it more legible and available for future, more efficient taxation. It is a strategic gift that paves the way for future taking.</p><h4><strong>The Downward Pressure: Cannibalizing the Base</strong></h4><p>For every upward flow of resources, there must be a corresponding downward pressure. The other side of the legislative equation reveals the brutal mechanics of cannibalization. The "historic cuts" to the nation's primary safety nets, Medicaid and food stamps, represent the most direct form of this internal consumption. The introduction of federally mandated work requirements is not a good-faith effort to promote employment; it is a classic bureaucratic barrier, a tool designed to increase administrative friction and disqualify recipients, thus cutting program costs and transferring the burden of survival directly onto the most vulnerable. As the Penn Wharton analysis shows, the result is a direct, measurable reduction in the after-tax, after-transfer income of the lowest-income Americans.</p><p>This assault on the base is accompanied by the deliberate weakening of the institutions that support it. The reduction in federal support for Medicaid enrollees and the tightening of verification requirements for Affordable Care Act subsidies directly attack the societal immune system. This inevitably creates more "uncompensated care costs," a burden that is then shunted onto community hospitals. These institutions, already under strain, are further weakened, diminishing access to care for everyone. The Congressional Budget Office forecast of "10 million more people being uninsured" is not an unfortunate side effect; it is a quantifiable measure of the system consuming its own capacity for public health.</p><p>Finally, the bill demonstrates the ultimate form of cannibalization: the consumption of the future to pay for the present. By stripping tax incentives for clean energy and electric vehicles, the legislation actively sabotages the nation's long-term energy resilience and a transition to a potentially higher-EROI paradigm. This is done to protect the short-term profits of the incumbent, and declining, hydrocarbon industry. More profoundly, the addition of $3.4 trillion to the national debt is a direct transfer of wealth from future generations to current asset holders. This borrowing ensures higher interest rates, making life more expensive for future citizens and businesses, and locking the state into a death spiral of debt service. The fact that national interest payments are set to surpass the entire defense budget is a clear signal of a system collapsing under the weight of its own fictitious claims on the future.</p><h4><strong>The Unmistakable Signature</strong></h4><p>Examined in its totality, this bill is not an anomaly. It is not an example of "bad policy" that can be corrected with minor tweaks. It is a perfect specimen of a system operating with flawless precision according to the terminal logic of the Axiom of Asymmetry. Every major provision maps directly onto the principles of the Cannibalization Imperative: concentrate wealth at the top; dismantle the commons and safety nets at the bottom; weaken foundational social institutions; and finance the present by strip-mining the future. It is a legislative act of self-consumption.</p><p>This real-world example serves as the final, incontrovertible proof for the arguments of this essay. It confirms that the abstract theories of collapse are, in fact, the day-to-day operating manual of modern governance. The legislative process, far from being a deliberative exercise in creating public good, is revealed here as a primary mechanism for enacting the axiom's brutal logic. The article is a real-time dispatch from the terminal phase, a tangible and undeniable demonstration that makes the theoretical discussion of systemic failure immediate, concrete, and unavoidable.</p><p></p><div class="subscription-widget-wrap-editor" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;en&quot;}" data-component-name="SubscribeWidgetToDOM"><div class="subscription-widget show-subscribe"><div class="preamble"><p class="cta-caption">Thanks for reading Sophia! Subscribe for free to receive new posts and support my work.</p></div><form class="subscription-widget-subscribe"><input type="email" class="email-input" name="email" placeholder="Type your email&#8230;" tabindex="-1"><input type="submit" class="button primary" value="Subscribe"><div class="fake-input-wrapper"><div class="fake-input"></div><div class="fake-button"></div></div></form></div></div><p></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/p/the-axiom-of-economic-asymmetry/comments&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Leave a comment&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/p/the-axiom-of-economic-asymmetry/comments"><span>Leave a comment</span></a></p><p></p>After the Truth Wars: The Three Roles of Truth-Makers Going ForwardSection I: From Attitude to Architecturehttps://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/p/after-the-truth-wars-the-three-roleshttps://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/p/after-the-truth-wars-the-three-rolesGeoffrey DucharmeThu, 03 Jul 2025 14:26:13 GMT<div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-img" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset image2-full-screen"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,w_5760,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:false,&quot;imageSize&quot;:&quot;full&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:971,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:490647,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/heic&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:&quot;https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/i/167201542?img=https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic&quot;,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:&quot;center&quot;,&quot;offset&quot;:false}" class="sizing-fullscreen" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vZJC!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd63f68e6-a359-45d0-bbab-f81747087fac_1536x1024.heic 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><div class="pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset"><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container restack-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-refresh-cw"><path d="M3 12a9 9 0 0 1 9-9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1 6.74 2.74L21 8"></path><path d="M21 3v5h-5"></path><path d="M21 12a9 9 0 0 1-9 9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1-6.74-2.74L3 16"></path><path d="M8 16H3v5"></path></svg></div><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container view-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p></p><h3><strong>Section I: From Attitude to Architecture</strong></h3><p>In our previous exploration, we established the Stability-Truth Tradeoff (STT) as a core diagnostic tool for understanding our polarized age. We identified the profound danger of the &#8220;triple myth&#8221;&#8212;the interlocking illusions at the personal, tribal, and institutional levels that make our society dangerously brittle in the face of reality. Yet, diagnosis is not destiny. Having mapped the landscape of our predicament and proposed the humble, truth-seeking attitude required to navigate it, we now face a new imperative. The question is no longer simply <em>what</em> is wrong, or even <em>how</em> we should feel about it. The urgent, constructive question now is: <strong>What do we build?</strong></p><p>As a foundation for this architectural work, let us revisit our central model. The STT posits that a truth is integrated only when its Perceived Value (V(T)) outweighs its Perceived Cost of Destabilization (C(S)). The <strong>Value of Truth</strong> is not a simple measure of factual accuracy; it is a composite of potential gains: the <strong>instrumental</strong> advantage a truth provides, the <strong>moral</strong> satisfaction of aligning with one's values, the <strong>social</strong> capital earned within a respected group, and the <strong>psychological</strong>coherence it lends to our self-image. Weighing against this is the <strong>Cost of Stability Loss</strong>, a force often linked to our deepest survival instincts. This cost includes the psychic pain of <strong>identity destabilization</strong>, the primal fear of <strong>social exile</strong>, the burden of confronting unbearable <strong>emotional pain</strong>, and the tangible threat of <strong>material consequence</strong>. Our analysis has shown that this cost is often the decisive factor, meaning our primary lever for change is not to inflate truth's value, but to thoughtfully and systematically lower the cost of its arrival.</p><p>To build durable structures, therefore, we must first be precise about what it is we are trying to protect and fortify: stability itself. In this context, stability is not the brittle rigidity of a system that denies reality to maintain its form, but the <strong>dynamic, resilient equilibrium</strong> of a system that can absorb shock and metabolize truth into strength. Each of the costs we've identified targets a fundamental layer of this stability. The fear of identity destabilization threatens our <strong>psychological</strong> coherence. The risk of social exile assails our <strong>social</strong> foundation of belonging. Even our very ability to reason is a form of <strong>neurobiological</strong> stability, a state of regulation that can be instantly short-circuited when a truth triggers a primal threat response. Our architecture must provide support at every one of these levels.</p><p>If stability is the structure we aim to build, then truth is its most challenging raw material. Like stability, truth is not a monolith, and the blueprints we draw must account for its varied forms. There is <strong>objective truth</strong>&#8212;scientific data, historical facts&#8212;which often threatens institutional narratives and economic models. There is <strong>subjective or emotional truth</strong>, such as the acknowledgement of personal trauma, which can destabilize our core identity and family systems. And finally, there is <strong>intersubjective truth</strong>, the shared myths and sacred stories that create cultural cohesion, whose deconstruction can feel like the dissolution of reality itself. A society capable of growth must build containers strong enough to hold all three.</p><p>With our diagnostic tool sharpened by these deeper definitions and our core materials&#8212;truth and stability&#8212;understood in their full complexity, our central task comes into focus. This essay will lay out the blueprints for a new, truth-bearing social architecture. It will detail the specific, practical strategies, from neurobiologically-informed communication protocols to error-tolerant institutional models, that can systematically lower the costs of destabilization across every layer of human experience. We will now move beyond the call for a new mindset and begin the tangible work of designing the rooms, halls, and public squares in which truth can be received, wept over, and finally, inhabited.</p><h3><strong>II. The Architecture of Fear: Deconstructing the Cost of Destabilization</strong></h3><p>Before we can build, we must excavate. The architectural challenge of creating truth-bearing systems requires us to first understand the foundations of the structures we seek to renovate: the human nervous system, the psyche, and the social fabric. The "Cost of Destabilization" (C(S)) is not a vague or abstract concept; it is a cascade of threats, experienced at every level of our being. To dismiss resistance to truth as mere ignorance or malice is to fundamentally misunderstand this architecture of fear. By mapping its layers in detail, we can appreciate the profound need for the scaffolding we intend to build.</p><p>The first and most fundamental cost is registered not in the conscious mind, but in the body. This is the <strong>neurobiological threat</strong>. Drawing on the work of Stephen Porges, we can understand this through the lens of <em>neuroception</em>&#8212;our nervous system&#8217;s subconscious surveillance system, which constantly scans our environment for cues of safety or danger. A truth that threatens our identity, belonging, or worldview is not processed as neutral data; it is perceived by the nervous system as a predator. The result is a physiological state of emergency:</p><ul><li><p>The amygdala triggers a primal alarm, flooding the body with stress hormones.</p></li><li><p>This activates a <strong>fight, flight, or freeze</strong> response.</p></li><li><p>Critically, this state of threat takes the prefrontal cortex&#8212;the seat of reason, nuance, and receptive learning&#8212;<strong>offline</strong>.</p></li></ul><p>In short, the body can veto a truth before the conscious mind even has a chance to consider it. You cannot reason with a nervous system that has already declared a state of war.</p><p>If the nervous system is the first line of defense, the psyche is the second. This is the <strong>psychological threat</strong>. Our identity is a complex narrative we construct to make sense of the world and our place in it. A destabilizing truth threatens to shatter this narrative, triggering what feels like an "ego death." This is more than just cognitive dissonance; it is a threat to the mind&#8217;s entire operating system, and the brain resists the immense energy expenditure required to rebuild a core worldview. Furthermore, as thinkers like Gabor Mat&#233; illustrate, many of our most rigid beliefs are not intellectual positions but sophisticated psychological defenses&#8212;scar tissue formed over old wounds. A truth that touches one of these wounds is not information; it is a re-triggering event, and the psyche will mobilize all its resources to repel it.</p><p>Zooming out from the individual, we encounter the third layer of cost: the <strong>social threat</strong>. Humans are ultra-social animals, and for millennia, exile from the tribe was a death sentence. Our brains are still wired to treat this possibility with existential terror. For many, belonging is conditional on believing. To accept a truth that contradicts the core tenets of one's family, religion, political party, or community is to risk ridicule, ostracization, and excommunication. As Ren&#233; Girard&#8217;s work on scapegoating suggests, groups often maintain their internal cohesion by projecting anxieties and contradictions onto a designated dissenter. The truth-teller who exposes the group&#8217;s sacred illusions is a prime candidate for this role. The defining question, therefore, is often not "Is this true?" but "<strong>Will believing this get me cast out?</strong>"</p><p>Finally, this fear is reinforced and amplified at the <strong>systemic threat</strong> level. Our institutions&#8212;governments, corporations, academic bodies&#8212;are built on foundational premises and narratives. A truth that invalidates a core premise threatens not just a policy, but the institution's entire claim to legitimacy. Beyond these formal structures lie our "invisible institutions": the great cultural narratives of meritocracy, national innocence, or perpetual progress. A truth that falsifies one of these sacred stories destabilizes the shared reality of millions. Today, this entire system is supercharged by our information architecture. The filter bubbles and algorithmic echo chambers described by Eli Pariser are not neutral platforms; they are systemic C(S)-reduction machines, explicitly designed to shield us from challenging information and thus systematically atrophy our collective capacity to handle truth.</p><p>This, then, is the terrain of resistance we face. It is a cascading threat that begins as a tremor in the nervous system, becomes a psychic earthquake in the self, threatens to cast us out from our tribe, and can shake the foundations of our societal reality. It is not a fortress of ignorance to be stormed, but a landscape of legitimate fear to be navigated with care. Only by understanding this intricate architecture of fear can we begin to design an architecture of hope.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-img" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,w_2400,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic" width="1200" height="800.2747252747253" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:false,&quot;imageSize&quot;:&quot;large&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:971,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:1200,&quot;bytes&quot;:428953,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/heic&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:&quot;https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/i/167201542?img=https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic&quot;,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:&quot;center&quot;,&quot;offset&quot;:false}" class="sizing-large" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qT8E!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc21a3edd-bef6-4034-867e-e6d2868bf3b5_1536x1024.heic 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><div class="pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset"><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container restack-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-refresh-cw"><path d="M3 12a9 9 0 0 1 9-9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1 6.74 2.74L21 8"></path><path d="M21 3v5h-5"></path><path d="M21 12a9 9 0 0 1-9 9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1-6.74-2.74L3 16"></path><path d="M8 16H3v5"></path></svg></div><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container view-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p></p><h3><strong>III. The Architect's Toolkit: Building Multi-Level Scaffolding</strong></h3><p>If Section II mapped the architecture of fear, this section provides the blueprints for an architecture of hope. Having excavated the landscape of legitimate resistance, we can now begin the work of construction. The following strategies are not abstract ideals but practical forms of scaffolding, meticulously designed to lower the Cost of Destabilization (C(S)) at every level of human experience. The goal is not to eliminate the cost of truth&#8212;some truths are inherently painful&#8212;but to build structures that help us bear that cost together, making the vital work of metabolizing reality possible.</p><h4><strong>&#128737;&#65039; 1. The Foundation: Building Relational Safety Before Intellectual Challenge</strong></h4><p>The first and most foundational layer of our architecture addresses the neurobiological and social threats directly. Before any difficult truth can be considered, the nervous system must be in a state of safety, and the individual must feel secure in their belonging. This is the non-negotiable prerequisite for all other work.</p><p>We build this safety through specific, practical techniques designed to signal security to the deepest parts of our brain. Consider <strong>Dialogue Circles</strong>. Unlike a debate, which is a zero-sum game structured for intellectual combat, a dialogue circle is a positive-sum game structured for mutual understanding. By enforcing simple rules&#8212;such as turn-taking, speaking from personal experience ("I" statements), and listening without interruption&#8212;the circle physically embodies respect. This structure tells the nervous system that this is a low-threat environment, keeping the prefrontal cortex online and available for complex thought.</p><p>An even more potent technique is the <strong>&#8220;Double-Listening&#8221; Protocol</strong>. This practice requires a listener to do more than just wait for their turn to speak; it requires them to absorb, process, and then restate the other person&#8217;s worldview <em>to that person&#8217;s complete satisfaction</em>. The goal is for them to say, &#8220;Yes, that&#8217;s exactly it. You understand.&#8221; This act of profound validation is a powerful de-escalator. It sends an undeniable signal: <em>I am willing to enter your world before I ask you to consider mine. Your perspective has value, and your humanity is not contingent on your agreement with me.</em> This single act dramatically lowers the social cost of the conversation by proving that disagreement will not lead to dismissal or exile. By creating this secure base of relational safety, we lower the C(S) by ensuring that truth, however difficult, does not cost a person their safety or their place in the tribe.</p><h4><strong>&#129496;&#8205;&#9794;&#65039; 2. The Inner Structure: Strengthening Internal Resilience and Identity Fluidity</strong></h4><p>With a safe container established, we can turn to the inner structure: the self. To counter the psychological threat of "ego death," we must help cultivate an identity that can bend without breaking. A fragile, rigid identity&#8212;one that is fused with its beliefs&#8212;will shatter on contact with a destabilizing truth. A flexible, resilient identity can adapt and integrate it. This is not an innate quality but a skill that can be cultivated through a range of practices.</p><p><strong>Contemplative practices</strong> like mindfulness meditation are a direct training in this skill. They teach us to observe our thoughts and beliefs as transient mental events, rather than as the unshakeable core of who we are. This creates a crucial gap between "I" and "my ideas," allowing for a sense of self that persists even when a cherished belief is challenged.</p><p>Therapeutic modalities like <strong>Internal Family Systems (IFS)</strong> take this a step further. IFS reframes the psyche not as a single, threatened monolith, but as a system of interacting "parts," each with its own history and positive intent. A challenging truth is then no longer an attack on "me," but an event that activates a specific, understandable part&#8212;a frightened "child" part, a protective "manager" part, or a reactive "firefighter" part. By learning to relate to these parts with curiosity and compassion, we can understand <em>why</em> a certain truth feels so threatening and work with that part instead of fighting against the truth itself.</p><p>Modern practices like <strong>psychedelic integration circles</strong> also function as a form of this scaffolding. After a profound, often identity-dissolving experience, these groups provide a structured environment to help individuals make sense of what they encountered, metabolizing destabilizing insights into a new, more expansive but still coherent sense of self. All these methods work to lower the identity collapse component of C(S), building a core self strong enough that it no longer needs outer illusions to stay coherent.</p><h4><strong>&#127963;&#65039; 3. The Public Square: Creating Institutions That Can Admit Error Without Collapsing</strong></h4><p>Next, we must scale this work from the individual to our collective systems. Institutions, like individuals, resist truth because they are designed for self-preservation. Admitting a foundational error often risks a catastrophic loss of credibility, leading to collapse. To lower this systemic C(S), we must decouple error from existential failure by intentionally designing <strong>error-tolerant systems</strong>.</p><p>This involves creating new protocols and incentives. We can build <strong>&#8220;confession protocols,&#8221;</strong> like the "no-blame" black box analysis in aviation, where the goal of investigating a failure is explicitly defined as collective learning, not individual punishment. This creates a culture where bringing a problem to light is seen as an act of service, not betrayal. We can <strong>invert institutional incentives</strong>, moving from a model that rewards confident truth-defense to one that rewards humble truth-correction. Imagine a scientific or policy journal where the most prestigious prize is awarded not for a groundbreaking paper, but for the most rigorous and consequential retraction of one's own previous work.</p><p>Furthermore, we can practice <strong>institutional storytelling</strong> that reframes the narrative of failure. Instead of burying past mistakes, institutions can actively memorialize them as crucibles of wisdom that made the system stronger and more resilient. South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission stands as a world-changing example of an institution built specifically for this purpose&#8212;to hold a nation's most destabilizing truths in a container of ritual, testimony, and amnesty. It proved that, with the right design, even entire societies can survive&#8212;and be healed by&#8212;their most painful realities.</p><h4><strong>&#127917; &amp; &#128257; 4. The Art of Assembly: Master Principles of Delivery</strong></h4><p>Finally, two master principles govern the <em>art of assembly</em> for this entire toolkit. These are not scaffolds themselves, but the methods for using them effectively.</p><p>The first is to <strong>Introduce Truth Symbolically, Not Just Logically</strong>. The conscious mind, the ego&#8217;s guard, is adept at arguing with data and deflecting literal propositions. The unconscious mind, however, speaks the language of story, metaphor, and myth. Art, drama, and parables can "pre-digest" a destabilizing reality by embedding it in a narrative structure. This bypasses the ego's direct confrontation, allowing a truth to enter softly, like water seeping through cracks in a foundation. It lands in the emotional and archetypal centers of the brain first, where it can be felt and processed before it is intellectually analyzed.</p><p>The second principle is to <strong>Design Gradual Threshold Transitions</strong>. Sudden truth shocks induce collapse; incremental exposure builds tolerance. This is the practice of <strong>"epistemic stair-stepping."</strong> We begin with what is already half-known or suspected and gently expand the frame, nesting a destabilizing idea within a familiar context. For example, instead of declaring a sacred cultural story "a lie," we might first introduce the idea that all cultures have foundational myths that serve a purpose, and then explore what purpose ours has served. This allows a person or a system to adapt over time, building the capacity to hold more complexity, rather than breaking under the force of a single, catastrophic revelation. As a rule, gradualists convert more minds than revolutionaries because they honor the system's need for continuity even as they invite it to change.</p><p>This toolkit&#8212;grounded in safety, fortified by a resilient self, scaled to our institutions, and delivered with artistry and patience&#8212;forms the core of our architectural project. These strategies do not make truth painless, but they make it bearable. They are the work of creating a world with the capacity to grow.</p><p></p><h3><strong>IV. The Architect's Dilemma: Power, Ethics, and the Shadow Side of Scaffolding</strong></h3><p>Any powerful tool can be misused, and any elegant model can shatter against the messy backdrop of human reality. Having laid out the architect's toolkit, we must now turn a critical eye upon it. A responsible architect understands not only how to build but also how their designs might fail, be co-opted, or prove inadequate. The Stability-Truth Tradeoff is not a panacea, but a framework that operates within complex systems fraught with power imbalances, moral emergencies, and the potential for manipulation. To apply it wisely, we must first confront its shadows.</p><p>The first and most significant dilemma arises in the face of <strong>power asymmetry</strong>. The STT model, in its ideal form, presumes a good-faith encounter where both parties have some shared interest in arriving at a more accurate map of reality. But what happens when one party has no interest in truth, only in maintaining control? In oppressive systems&#8212;be it an abusive family, a totalitarian state, or a colonial regime&#8212;the dominant party isn't just ignoring the Cost of Destabilization; they are actively and intentionally <strong>weaponizing it</strong> against the subordinate party. Truth-telling is not merely destabilizing; it is systematically punished with social, economic, or physical violence. In such a context, attempting to "build relational safety" is not only naive but potentially dangerous, as it asks the vulnerable party to open themselves up to an actor who has no intention of reciprocating. Here, the prerequisite for truth is not more scaffolding, but the active dismantling of the oppressive power structure that makes truth-telling a suicidal act. The primary work is not one of therapy, but of liberation.</p><p>The second dilemma pits the model&#8217;s preference for patience against the <strong>moral imperative of urgency</strong>. The principle of gradual, incremental truth-telling is wise when the primary risk is systemic shock. But what about when the primary risk is the catastrophic cost of inaction? When facing a climate tipping point, an unfolding genocide, or a rapidly metastasizing social injustice, the slow, patient work of the gradualist can become a form of moral complicity. This forces us to expand our calculus. The STT model focuses on the C(S) of telling the truth, but we must weigh it against the C(S) of <em>not</em> telling it&#8212;the cost of maintaining a false and fatal stability. At certain "Kairos" moments, a "truth shock" may be the only responsible, ethical act, even if it guarantees instability. The wisdom for the architect lies in discerning when to be a patient gardener tending to the soil and when to be a firefighter sounding a five-alarm fire.</p><p>The third and most insidious dilemma is the <strong>co-opting of safety</strong> to create a more resilient form of delusion. The very tools of the STT toolkit can be perverted to build a more comfortable and impenetrable echo chamber. This is the shadow side of our model, where scaffolding becomes a cage.</p><ul><li><p><strong>Relational safety</strong> can be twisted into conditional belonging: "You are safe and loved here <em>as long as you conform</em>."</p></li><li><p>The language of therapy and vulnerability can be weaponized to <strong>pathologize dissent</strong>: "Your disagreement isn't a valid intellectual point; it's just your trauma speaking."</p></li><li><p>This dynamic is perfected in <strong>high-control groups and cults</strong>. They are masters of the STT model. They create immense relational safety and a powerful sense of purpose (lowering the C(S) for staying), while simultaneously inflating the C(S) for leaving with threats of shunning, spiritual damnation, and social annihilation.</p></li></ul><p>The ultimate measure of healthy scaffolding is whether it increases a system's capacity to engage with <strong>challenging, external reality</strong>. If the tools are instead used to build a more comfortable bunker shielded <em>from</em> reality, they have become part of the problem. This is the difference between a greenhouse that nurtures growth into the open air and a hermetically sealed biosphere that slowly suffocates its inhabitants.</p><p>These dilemmas do not invalidate our model, but they demand a higher level of awareness from those who would use it. The responsible architect must approach their work not with a simple checklist, but with a constant and critical self-interrogation. They must ask: <em>Who bears the cost of this truth? Who bears the cost of this stability? And is the scaffolding I am building serving liberation or containment?</em> This ethical vigilance is what separates a wise builder from a naive one, and it is essential as we turn to the final, motivational aspect of our framework.</p><p></p><h3><strong>V. The Other Side of the Equation: Elevating the Value of Truth (Polished Version)</strong></h3><p>Our focus, thus far, has been on the crucial work of structural engineering&#8212;of laying foundations and erecting scaffolding to make our dwellings safe for the seismic shocks of reality. We have learned to be compassionate architects, designing systems to lower the formidable Cost of Destabilization. Yet, a house, however safe, is not yet a home. It needs light, art, and purpose to become a place one longs to be. Some truths carry a cost so high that no amount of reinforcement can make them welcome. In these moments, we must put down our hammers and pick up our paintbrushes. We must now turn to the other side of the STT equation: the fine art of magnifying the Perceived Value of Truth (V(T)). This is the craft of illumination, of framing truth not as a bitter pill, but as a masterpiece of liberation so profound that it becomes a treasure worth the quest.</p><p>The first brushstroke is to <strong>frame truth as a landscape of liberation</strong>. This is the art of alchemical transformation, turning the leaden weight of pain into the golden light of purpose. We take the raw, jagged material of emotional distress and sculpt it into a key. The central, creative question we pose is, "What if this pain is not a wall, but a doorway?" By framing a crisis not as a collapse but as the cracking of a beautiful, hand-painted shell that has grown too small, we imbue the process with aesthetic dignity. The anxiety we feel is no longer a flaw in the design, but the vibrant, creative tension just before a masterpiece is revealed&#8212;the sign that a more expansive and authentic life is waiting to be unveiled. This artistry transforms truth from a destructive force into a chisel, skillfully wielded to chip away the plaster and reveal the breathtaking form that was always waiting within.</p><p>Next, our artistry must be grounded in realism. We must learn to <strong>illuminate the crumbling architecture of illusion</strong>. The false stability offered by a comforting lie is a poorly constructed facade. From a distance, it may look solid, but up close, we can reveal the hairline fractures, the slow decay, the high-interest loan from reality that will eventually bring the whole structure down. Our task as artists is to shine a harsh, diagnostic light on this decay, making the future cost vivid and present. We paint a portrait of the personal cost: the dull, graying tones of a life lived inauthentically, the slow poisoning of relationships built on pretense. We create a mural of the societal cost: the erosion of civic trust as a slow-motion demolition of our public squares. We sculpt a monument to the ecological cost, showing how the short-term comfort of denial is paid for with the inheritance of our children. This artistry reframes the choice. It is no longer "A Safe, Familiar Room vs. A Perilous Journey," but rather, "A Condemned Building vs. The Chance to Build Anew on Solid Ground."</p><p>The most powerful act of illumination, however, is to <strong>connect truth to the sublime</strong>. This is the art of the cathedral-builder, moving beyond mere function to touch the transcendent. Facts are stone, but meaning is stained glass, transforming mere data into breathtaking light. As the saying goes, "People don't die for facts. They die for meaning." Our final and most important work is to hang truth in this cathedral of human values. The scientist who endures ridicule for a revolutionary theory is not just defending data; she is a guardian of the elegant, cosmic order she has glimpsed. The activist who risks everything for a social truth is not just correcting an injustice; he is an artist painting a future where human dignity is the central subject. The parent who speaks a difficult family truth is not causing a wound, but performing a loving, painful act of kintsugi&#8212;mending the family's broken pottery with gold, making it stronger and more beautiful than before.</p><p>Finally, we must recognize that this artistry creates a beautiful <strong>resonance</strong>, turning a solo performance into a choir. An individual's embrace of a costly truth is never a single, isolated note; it creates a harmonic that empowers others to find their own voice. When one person dares to sing their truth, they carve a new sonic pathway, making it easier for others to join the chorus. This transforms the V(T) equation into a crescendo. It adds the profound social value of being a composer for one's tribe, a first voice whose courage makes a symphony possible. The Perceived Value of Truth is multiplied by the number of voices it ultimately liberates.</p><p>By learning to be both compassionate engineers <em>and</em> inspired artists&#8212;by both lowering the cost of truth's arrival and amplifying its profound beauty&#8212;we complete our architectural vision. We are now equipped not just to build a safe room, but to furnish it with light and art, making it a place people desperately want to enter, knowing that the beauty they find inside is worth the pilgrimage.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-img" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!_XJ3!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F074cf117-6e10-4ca7-8bf1-780f95377126_1536x1024.heic" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!_XJ3!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F074cf117-6e10-4ca7-8bf1-780f95377126_1536x1024.heic 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!_XJ3!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F074cf117-6e10-4ca7-8bf1-780f95377126_1536x1024.heic 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!_XJ3!,w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F074cf117-6e10-4ca7-8bf1-780f95377126_1536x1024.heic 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!_XJ3!,w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F074cf117-6e10-4ca7-8bf1-780f95377126_1536x1024.heic 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!_XJ3!,w_2400,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F074cf117-6e10-4ca7-8bf1-780f95377126_1536x1024.heic" width="1200" height="800.2747252747253" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/074cf117-6e