%2Fimages%2F625b3492-3d58-44cd-aaf1-0db9dc317dfa_1536x1024.heic&quot;,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:&quot;center&quot;,&quot;offset&quot;:false}" class="sizing-fullscreen" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!VrGX!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F625b3492-3d58-44cd-aaf1-0db9dc317dfa_1536x1024.heic 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!VrGX!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F625b3492-3d58-44cd-aaf1-0db9dc317dfa_1536x1024.heic 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!VrGX!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F625b3492-3d58-44cd-aaf1-0db9dc317dfa_1536x1024.heic 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!VrGX!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F625b3492-3d58-44cd-aaf1-0db9dc317dfa_1536x1024.heic 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><div class="pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset"><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container restack-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-refresh-cw"><path d="M3 12a9 9 0 0 1 9-9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1 6.74 2.74L21 8"></path><path d="M21 3v5h-5"></path><path d="M21 12a9 9 0 0 1-9 9 9.75 9.75 0 0 1-6.74-2.74L3 16"></path><path d="M8 16H3v5"></path></svg></div><div class="pencraft pc-reset icon-container view-image"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>A few days ago, I was on a thread with AI about a few things, namely sycophancy in AI. </p><p>Then, I noted that, as a society and in general, we humans prefer the comforting lies until such point that either the cost of the lie is too great to be ignored, or there is an easy fix that allows for the lie to be taken down. </p><div class="subscription-widget-wrap-editor" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;en&quot;}" data-component-name="SubscribeWidgetToDOM"><div class="subscription-widget show-subscribe"><div class="preamble"><p class="cta-caption">Thanks for reading Sophia! Subscribe for free to receive new posts and support my work.</p></div><form class="subscription-widget-subscribe"><input type="email" class="email-input" name="email" placeholder="Type your email&#8230;" tabindex="-1"><input type="submit" class="button primary" value="Subscribe"><div class="fake-input-wrapper"><div class="fake-input"></div><div class="fake-button"></div></div></form></div></div><p>The best example here is Ozempic. Before the drug, there were deceitful social movements that claimed that health was possible at any size. There were campaigns and even glorification of the larger bodies on multiple medias. However, as soon as the drug became part of our social awareness, the need for the lie about body size disappeared.</p><p>The same thing happens in many spheres of our lives, and the title of the post should give a clue on the particular that are at stake. </p><p>Originally, AI called it relationship decay, which is apt enough, but I think relationship desertification is the better term. <br><br>Much like global warming, relationship decay is a slow and steady erosion of our society. Yet, it&#8217;s not the name or the effect that matters, but rather the continuous lie around it.</p><p>To quote our dear AI friend on this matter:</p><p><code>By relationship decay, I mean the widespread, often silent unraveling of deep, stable, emotionally nourishing relationships&#8212;romantic, familial, communal&#8212;across modern societies. It's a phenomenon that spans:</code></p><ul><li><p><code>&#128148; Romantic partnerships (declining marriage rates, rising divorce, sexlessness, ghosting)</code></p></li><li><p><code>&#128106; Family bonds (estrangement, lower birth rates, dissolving extended family roles)</code></p></li><li><p><code>&#129309; Friendship networks (epidemic of loneliness, superficial social media ties)</code></p></li><li><p><code>&#129517; Shared moral compass (value fragmentation, loss of intergenerational trust)</code></p></li></ul><p><code>And like the other domains we've discussed, there's a disconnect between what we privately experience and what we publicly admit.</code></p><p></p><p>While the emoticons add emphasis, I think it&#8217;s important for us to concentrate on the core of the message. This fragmentation and desertification is not new; Robert Putnam noted it back in 2000.</p><p>It&#8217;s part of the reason I wrote <strong>The Inner Sheep: Why fitting in is the new standing out.</strong> What is my concern now is that we seem to be getting to the point that even if we want to belong to a group, there is no more crowd to belong to. And that is deeply troubling.</p><p>With obesity, it was possible to imagine and eventually deliver a techno fix. It was about cellular pathways, understanding hunger signaling and using technology to replicate satiation.</p><p>With this relationship desertification, it&#8217;s not at all clear to me that technology can fix it. In fact, it seems that technology might be the cause of our issue. </p><p>Likewise, our friend the AI agrees on the challenge ahead.<br><br><code>&#129504; What would count as a &#8220;remedy&#8221;?</code></p><p><code>This is tricky&#8212;because unlike obesity or cognition, you can&#8217;t inject or train a relationship into existence. Still, some candidate levers might be:</code></p><ul><li><p><code>Mass-scale relational education (communication, conflict repair, intimacy skills)</code></p></li><li><p><code>AI-supported matchmaking with deep psych modeling (ethical minefield)</code></p></li><li><p><code>Community design that engineers real interdependence</code></p></li><li><p><code>Policy that rewards relational investment, not just GDP contribution</code></p></li></ul><p><code>Until such levers exist and gain traction, we&#8217;ll likely continue pretending the decay is just a &#8220;natural evolution of culture.&#8221;</code></p><p></p><p>I&#8217;m not pretending anymore. I know that things have changed. That it&#8217;s much harder than it used to be to make friends. That people have their eyes in their phones and headphones in their ears. That our common values are not shared to the same extent. That there is not much point in screaming in the digital ether, because it&#8217;s not what&#8217;s selected for in our attention economy.</p><p>The solutions AI has noted above do not seem likely to come about until we acknowledge the deep social issue we face on this point.</p><p>But what gives me comfort is this. I know I&#8217;m not the only one that feels alone. Now, I can&#8217;t wait for others to see it and want to change it.<br><br>In my next post, I&#8217;ll tackle what solutions actually look like in this field.</p><div class="subscription-widget-wrap-editor" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;en&quot;}" data-component-name="SubscribeWidgetToDOM"><div class="subscription-widget show-subscribe"><div class="preamble"><p class="cta-caption">Thanks for reading Sophia! Subscribe for free to receive new posts and support my work.</p></div><form class="subscription-widget-subscribe"><input type="email" class="email-input" name="email" placeholder="Type your email&#8230;" tabindex="-1"><input type="submit" class="button primary" value="Subscribe"><div class="fake-input-wrapper"><div class="fake-input"></div><div class="fake-button"></div></div></form></div></div>Coming soonThis is Sophia, a newsletter about Timeless Wisdom to Escape The Matrix.https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/p/coming-soonhttps://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/p/coming-soonGeoffrey DucharmeWed, 13 Apr 2022 12:47:10 GMT<p><strong>This is Sophia</strong>, a newsletter about Timeless Wisdom to Escape The Matrix.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://geoffreyducharme.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p>